# Overview

This project implements two core functionalities: graph node reordering based on the OCRH algorithm and cache performance measurement for diverse graph traversal algorithms.

## Project Structure
├── OCRH/                    # Traversal-based node ordering and clustering module
│   ├── OCRH_main.cpp              # Main program entry
│   ├── OCRH_traversal.cpp         # BFS/DFS/SSSP traversal implementations
│   ├── OCRH_csr_io.cpp            # CSR-format graph file I/O
│   ├── OCRH_kcmer_minhash.cpp      # k-cmer + MinHash feature extraction
│   ├── OCRH_clustering.cpp        # k-means clustering implementation
│   ├── OCRH_graph_common.h        # Header file (data structures and definitions)
│   └── Makefile                   # Build script
│
└── traversal/              # Graph traversal cache performance analysis module
    ├── traversal_main.cpp          # Main program entry
    ├── traversal_traversal.cpp     # BFS/DFS/SSSP/WCC/PageRank/Diameter implementations
    ├── traversal_cache_perf.cpp    # Cache performance statistics and measurement
    ├── traversal_csr_io.cpp        # CSR-format graph file I/O
    ├── traversal_utils.cpp         # Utility functions
    ├── traversal_graph_common.h    # Header file (data structures and definitions)
    └── Makefile                    # Build script

Module 1: OCRH-based Graph Reordering & Clustering
  This module implements graph reordering based on the OCRH algorithm. It uses BFS/DFS/SSSP traversals to generate node sequences, extracts k-mer and MinHash features, and applies k-means clustering to produce an optimized node order.
  
  Compilation
    cd OCRH 
    make
  
  Usage
    ./OCRH <graph_file> <topk> <x> <k_clusters> <traversal_type> <-large/-small>
    nohup ./OCRH <graph_file> <topk> <x> <k_clusters> <traversal_type> <-large/-small> > run.log 2>&1 &   
  
  Parameter Explanation:
    <graph_file>:       Input graph in CSR binary format (.csr)
    <topk>:             Number of top high-degree nodes used as traversal sources
    <x>:                Number of candidate centers for k-means clustering
    <k_clusters>:       Number of clusters for node grouping
    <traversal_type>:   0=BFS, 1=DFS, 2=SSSP
    <-large/-small>:    Mode for large/small graph memory optimization
  
  Important Notes:
    - The OCRH module requires .csr format graph files as input.
  
  Outputs:  
    This module outputs the final reordered node sequence generated by the OCRH algorithm. If you run the program with nohup, detailed logs recording the elapsed time of each stage and key steps will also be generated.

Module 2: Graph Traversal Cache Performance Evaluation
  This module measures the cache performance of six common graph traversal algorithms, including BFS, DFS, SSSP, WCC, PageRank, and Diameter. It supports original order, random order, custom node order files, and can generate "Self Order" — the optimal node sequence based on each algorithm's own traversal.

  Compilation
    cd traversal
    make

  Usage
    ./traversal_perf <graph_file> <order_dir> <is_directed> <traversal_num>
    nohup ./traversal_perf <graph_file> <order_dir> <is_directed> <traversal_num> > run.log 2>&1 &

  Parameter Explanation:
    <graph_file>:      Input graph in CSR binary format (.csr)
    <order_dir>:       Directory containing custom node order files 
    <is_directed>:     0 = undirected graph, 1 = directed graph
    <traversal_num>:   1=BFS, 2=DFS, 3=SSSP, 4=WCC, 5=PageRank, 6=Diameter

  Important Notes:
    - This module accepts .txt format node order files as input, which are different from the .csr files used by the OCRH module.
    - You can place multiple order files in the specified directory; the program will evaluate all of them automatically.

  Outputs:
    This module outputs detailed cache performance metrics, including L1/L3 cache access counts, miss rates, and execution time for each traversal under different node orders. If you run the program with nohup, a full log of the process will also be saved.

## Test Dataset
You could adopt the Amazon co-purchase graph as the standard test dataset for algorithm validation and performance testing.
   download: 
        wget http://snap.stanford.edu/data/com-amazon.ungraph.txt.gz
        gunzip com-amazon.ungraph.txt.gz
This is an undirected graph, so you can use the -small parameter when running the OCRH module. You must convert the raw graph file into the .csr binary format before running the OCRH and traversal modules.   